Global Unicast Addresses (GUA)
Range: 2000::/3
Purpose: most of publicly routable addresses

Unique Local Addresses (ULA)
Range: fc00::/7 (for locally assigned, fc00::/8)
Purpose: IPv6 equivalent of private addresses, cannot be routed over internet

Link-Local Unicast Addresses
Range: fe80::/10
Purpose: Automatically assigned address to every IPv6 enabled interface, not routable

Multicast Addresses
Range: ff00::/8
Purpose: Used to send single streams to multiple destinations
ff02::1 All nodes(devices) on the local network segment
ff02::2 All routers on local network segment
Many more

Segment Routing
Range: 5f00:/16
Purpose: For segment routing SRv6

Discard Prefix
Range: 100::/64
Purpose: Discard prefix

Teredo Tunneling
Range: 2001::/32
Purpose: Teredo Tunneling

6to4 Addressing Scheme:
Range: 2002::/16
Purpose: 6to4 addressing scheme

Special and Loopback Addresses
Loopback Address
Range: ::1/128
Purpose: Used by a device to send traffic to itself

Unspecified Address
Range: ::/128
Purpose: Used by a host that doesn't have an IP address yet, during boot-up

Documentation Prefix:
Range: 2001:0db8::/32
Range: 3fff::/20
Purpose: Used in documentation, examples, and education tutorials

Transition and Translation Ranges
IPv4-Mapped Addresses:
Range: ::ffff:0:0/96
Purpose: Used to represent and IPv4 address within an IPv6 environment

NAT64/DNS64 Translation: 64:ff9b::/96
Purpose: Used to translate and map IPv4 packets to IPv6